Honestly this store/restaurant is more than I had expected. Service was amazing. When you enter it looks like a store not a restaurant.  The owners are so cool, and chill. Makes you feel like you’ve known them forever.  If it wasn’t for them closing, I think I would have stayed longer, but you know people have lives. Lol.  Food was great. I had a pesto California wrap.  Hands down the best wrap in my life.  It had pesto sauce, sun dried tomatoes, shredded chicken, drizzled with balsamic vinaigrette. We also a sangria. Delicious !  I would order this 20,000 more times.  I also bought this cute bracelet.  Love their accessories, candles and sage.

This place deserves 10 stars. Most places seem to have forgotten what good service resembles but this place didn't. Damien (who served as our host, waiter, chef, and busboy) is seriously an amazing person. Other than the fact that this was the most delicious brunch we've had in years, the sweet and kind service will be bringing us back for sure (and also the delicious sangria). Hom is fantastic. The staff is welcoming, the food is delicious, and the shop itself is cozy and sweet.  I attended a birthday celebration there in which we had the place to ourselves (a large group), and watched a movie of our choosing. Hom has a screen and DVD player/projector, but be sure to bring your own projector and player if you'll be watching a Blu-Ray. It was $20 per person with unlimited popcorn, choice of drinks, and choice of entree, plus a small dessert.  They also have a retail section with tea, incense, jewelry, and more.  We had an amazing time and I highly recommend it.

Absolutely love the decor and the look and feel of this place. Eclectic kind of brunch spot. You'll find a interesting decor once you walk in and not know if you are in a antique shop or a restaurant. They sell artisinal home made items for your home hence the name hom. While the back area is the restaurant. Service was wonderful as they were very attentive and friendly. Standout dish was the corn beef hash with eggs and a biscuit. Biscuit was soft and buttery. As well as the bread basket which came with a variety of cakes and bagels. The whole meal was satisfactory but not overwhelmingly memorable. It's a great neighborhood spot though but wouldn't be a destination kind of place for me.

This is one of my favorite joints for brunch- just to escape the craziness of the city.  I've been here 4 times now.  I recently bought the $19 Groupon deal which covered a brunch dish plus a glass of sangria for 2.  It's a great steal considering their usual prices on the food ($12.95) and sangria ($10) per person.  If I had written this after the last time, it would have gotten a stellar 5 stars from me.  However, on my most recent visit, I ordered the same gingerbread pancakes.  The pancakes were shrunken in size, and were placed on an oval dish instead of the usual large, round one.  Also, they were not as fluffy as I had remembered, and they tasted drier than usual.  They were not as well executed.  I had to wonder if it was because the place was packed this time around- the first few times I went, there were only 2 or 3 tables filled.  It's not a big space to begin with; the front area is a store, which sells home goods and accessories.  They are only utilizing the back space as a cafe type environment.  I'm still giving it a high score for the culmination of my experiences thus far, and to give the benefit of the doubt that the last brunch was a one-time flop.  However, I won't be returning until they change their menu; I think I might be pancaked out.

I love coming here for brunch. On the weekends they'll even have a live musician come play and set a jazzy mood for the place. My friend got the hamburger and I had the burrito. Both were very good. I especially loved the tea which comes in a tea pot at your table. The gift store in the front is a great place to look for glittery gifts.
